Descriptive Statistics

Kevin Mackay

27/04/2021

SETUP

LOAD LIBRARIES

library(tidyverse)

IMPORT DATA

# This data set represents Trump's tweets between 2014 and 2021, starting when he publicly announced his presidential candidacy
tweets <- read_csv("trump_insult_tweets_2014_to_2021.csv")

CLEAN DATA

tweets$char_count <- lapply(tweets$tweet, str_length) # ADD CHARACTER COUNT COLUMN
tweets$char_count <- as.double(tweets$char_count)

tweets <- tweets %>%
  filter(!char_count > 280) # Remove tweets greater than Twitter's character limit

MEASURES OF CENTRAL TENDENCY

MODE

target <- tweets %>%
  group_by(target) %>%
  summarise(target_count = n()) %>%
  filter(target_count == max(target_count))

target
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   target    target_count
##   <chr>            <int>
## 1 the-media         1271

The most frequent target of Trump’s tweets during 2014 to 2021 was the-media, which was targeted 1271 times.

insult_word <- tweets %>%
  group_by(insult) %>%
  summarise(insult_count = n()) %>%
  filter(insult_count == max(insult_count))

insult_word
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   insult    insult_count
##   <chr>            <int>
## 1 Fake News          424

The most frequent insult of Trump’s tweets during 2014 to 2021 was Fake News, which was used 424 times.

tweet_length <- tweets %>%
  group_by(char_count) %>%
  summarise(times_used = n()) %>%
  filter(times_used == max(times_used))

tweet_length
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   char_count times_used
##        <dbl>      <int>
## 1        280        900

The most frequent character length of Trump’s tweet during 2014 to 2021 was 280, which was used 900 times.

FILTER ONLY UNIQUE TWEETS

unique_tweets <- tweets %>%
  select(tweet_date, tweet, char_count) %>%
  distinct()

MEAN

mean_chars <- unique_tweets %>%
  select(tweet_date, tweet, char_count) %>%
  summarise(mean_char = mean(char_count)) %>%
  round(digits = 2)

mean_chars
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   mean_char
##       <dbl>
## 1      190.

The average number of characters in Trump’s tweets during 2014 to 2021 was 189.8.

MEDIAN

med_chars <- unique_tweets %>%
  select(tweet_date, tweet, char_count) %>%
  summarise(med_char = median(char_count)) %>%
  round(digits = 2)

med_chars
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   med_char
##      <dbl>
## 1      173

The median number of characters in Trump’s tweets during 2014 ot 2021 was 173.

HISTOGRAM

ggplot(unique_tweets, aes(char_count)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(unique_tweets$char_count),        # Add line for mean (RED)
             col = "red",
             lwd = 1) +                                     
  geom_vline(xintercept = median(unique_tweets$char_count),      # Add line for median (BLUE)
             col = "blue",
             lwd = 1)

MEASURES OF DISPERSION

RANGE

tweet_chars_min <- min(unique_tweets$char_count)
tweet_chars_max <- max(unique_tweets$char_count)

# What tweet could possibly be only 11 characters by a president of the United States?
unique(unique_tweets$tweet[unique_tweets$char_count == 11])
## [1] "WITCH HUNT!"
range <- tweet_chars_max - tweet_chars_min
range
## [1] 269

The range of Trump’s tweet length is 269.

INTERQUARTILE RANGE

iqr <- unique_tweets %>%
  summarise(iqr_25 = quantile(char_count, 0.25), iqr_75 = quantile(char_count, 0.75))

iqr
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   iqr_25 iqr_75
##    <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1   135.    273

The interquartile range of Trump’s tweet lengths is 135.25 to 273.

BOXPLOT

ggplot(unique_tweets, aes(x = 0, y=char_count)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Trump's tweets, 2014 to 2021", y = "Character count of tweet")

STANDARD DEVIATION

# SAMPLE (Not every tweet by Trump)
std_tweet_count <- unique_tweets %>%
  summarise(std_dev = sd(char_count))

round(std_tweet_count, digits = 2)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   std_dev
##     <dbl>
## 1    73.8
?sd # Like var this uses denominator n - 1.
## starting httpd help server ... done

The standard deviation of tweet length was 73.7684333.

COEFFICIENT OF VARIATION

cov <- sd(unique_tweets$char_count) / mean(unique_tweets$char_count)
cov
## [1] 0.3886624

HISTOGRAM WITH STANDARD DEVIATION

ggplot(unique_tweets, aes(char_count)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(unique_tweets$char_count),        # Add line for mean (RED)
             col = "red",
             lwd = 1) +                                     
  geom_vline(xintercept = median(unique_tweets$char_count),      # Add line for median (BLUE)
             col = "blue",
             lwd = 1) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(unique_tweets$char_count) - sd(unique_tweets$char_count),      # Add line for lower SD
             col = "black",
             lwd = 1) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(unique_tweets$char_count) + sd(unique_tweets$char_count),      # Add line for upper SD
             col = "black",
             lwd = 1)

DEEPER DIVE

On November 7, 2017, Twitter increased its character limit from 140 to 280. How does Trump’s character count change between these two time periods?

tweets_140 <- unique_tweets %>%
  filter(tweet_date < "2017-11-07") %>%
  filter(char_count <= 140)

tweets_280 <- unique_tweets %>%
  filter(tweet_date >= "2017-11-07" & char_count <= 280)

MEAN

mean_chars_140 <- tweets_140 %>%
  select(tweet_date, tweet, char_count) %>%
  summarise(mean_chars_140 = mean(char_count)) %>%
  round(digits = 2)

mean_chars_280 <- tweets_280 %>%
  select(tweet_date, tweet, char_count) %>%
  summarise(mean_chars_280 = mean(char_count)) %>%
  round(digits = 2)

mean_chars
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   mean_char
##       <dbl>
## 1      190.
mean_chars_140
## # A tibble: 1 x 1

##            <dbl>
## 1           129.
mean_chars_280
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   mean_chars_280
##            <dbl>
## 1           221.

med_chars_140 <- tweets_140 %>%

COEFFICIENT OF VARIATION

## [1] "280:  0.33"
